128. ao. par et similis. These expressions are frequently used to· gether to express complete similarity in every respect. The difference between them is that por indicates the value‚ importance or power of a thing, similis its constitution, external or internal. Quintilian X, 1, 102 speaking of Sallust and Livy says that they were pares nitigis quam similes, ie. equal in worth, though different in character; and Seneca De Ira l, 9 speaking ol the passions says: quos (affectem) noctiquam deprimere possis, nisi pares illis similesque opposueris, ie. passions equally strong aud like in kind.
